his volume by Medvedkin himself, document for the first time his considerable achievements, experiments in film and theater, and attempts to develop satire as a major Soviet film genre. Through scripts, letters, autobiographical writings, and more, we see a Medvedkin supported and admired by figures like Eisenstein, Dovzhenko, and Maxim Gorky.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMedvedkin, Alexander. 0aMotion pictureszSoviet Union. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aAlexander Medvedkin.  aBolshevism.  aHappiness (film).  aJay Leyda.  aKino-Train.  aSoviet film.  acensorship and suppression.  adocumentary film.  aexperimental film.  asatire.1 aLary, Nikita.1 aLeyda, Jay.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226296302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226296302/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles